<sn><md>#### Contributions of the Phoenicians

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
In the history of ancient civilizations, the Phoenicians are regarded as some of the finest `sailors` and `shipbuilders`. They used the `North Star (Polaris)` to determine direction while navigating at sea. Because of this, the North Star was often referred to as the `Phoenician Star`.

:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://c02.purpledshub.com/uploads/sites/48/2024/11/ship-starry-night-sky.jpg?webp=1\&amp;w=1200)
:::
:::

```id="f8t2dw"
Phoenician Contributions
        |
        +--&gt; Sailors
        |
        +--&gt; Shipbuilders
        |
        +--&gt; Navigation using North Star
                |
                +--&gt; Direction finding
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Cultural Development

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
The greatest contribution of the Phoenicians in the history of civilization was the invention of the `alphabet`. They developed an alphabet consisting of `22 consonants`. This became the foundation of modern writing systems. Later, the `Greeks` added `vowels` to the Phoenician alphabet, completing it.
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://t3.ftcdn.net/jpg/13/72/05/70/360_F_1372057065_Vw82pROX9QlVeQITyOrj5EBN8d6AxLjE.jpg)
:::
:::



```id="s7q1lz"
Cultural Development
        |
        +--&gt; Alphabet
        |       |
        |       +--&gt; 22 consonants
        |
        +--&gt; Greek Addition
                |
                +--&gt; Vowels
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Technical Skills

The Phoenicians were skilled in producing `clay pottery`. They were also highly proficient in `weaving cloth` and `dyeing fabrics` with advanced craftsmanship.

```id="t6k3qp"
Technical Skills
        |
        +--&gt; Clay Pottery
        |
        +--&gt; Textile Production
                |
                +--&gt; Weaving
                +--&gt; Dyeing
```
</md></sn><sn><md>#### MCQ Solution

1. What is the greatest contribution of the Phoenicians in the history of civilization? (Department of Environment and Forest / Department of Labour / Islamic University) <br>
   **Answer: Alphabet**

2. Who first invented the alphabet? (Department of Mass Communication) <br>
   **Answer: Phoenicians**
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Summary

| Key                             | Information                                                                                                                                  |
| ------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Period**                      | Flourished around `c. 1500–300 BCE` (Phoenician dominance in the Mediterranean trade network)                                                |
| **Location**                    | Narrow coastal strip between the `Lebanon Mountains` and the `Mediterranean Sea`                                                             |
| **Modern Country**              | Present-day `Lebanon`, parts of `Syria` and `Israel/Palestine region`                                                                        |
| **Origin of Concept**           | Developed as a `maritime trading civilization` due to lack of fertile land and dependence on sea trade                                       |
| **Discovery**                   | Studied through ancient `Mediterranean records`, archaeological remains of cities like `Tyre`, `Sidon`, and `Byblos`                         |
| **Invention**                   | `Alphabet (22 consonants)`, foundation of modern writing systems                                                                             |
| **Contribution**                | Maritime trade, shipbuilding, navigation using the `North Star`, development of early alphabet system, craftsmanship in pottery and textiles |
| **Civilization Identification** | Known as the `Phoenician Civilization`                                                                                                       |
| **Religion**                    | `Polytheistic religion` (worship of nature and city-based deities like Baal)                                                                 |
| **Power System**                | City-state based system (independent cities like `Tyre`, `Sidon`, `Byblos` rather than a unified empire)                                     |
| **Population**                  | Small coastal population focused mainly on `trade, navigation, and craftsmanship`                                                            |
| **Famous Personalities**        | No single central ruler recorded; known cities include `Hiram I of Tyre` (important king of Tyre)                                            |
</md></sn>